As of my last update in October 2023, Google Maps does not have a publicly documented "time travel" endpoint. If you are referring to visualizing historical imagery or viewing past states of map data, this typically falls outside the API's publicly available features. Many functionalities are part of the Google Earth Engine or are available directly on the Google Maps interface but not through an API.

However, if you are looking to implement a feature that uses a similar form of functionality, you might need to pivot to using existing APIs like:

1. Google Maps JavaScript API for displaying maps.
2. Image overlays or custom tilesets for historical data (if you have access to historical imagery).

Here's an example of how you might set up a basic Google Maps instance using the Google Maps JavaScript API:

### Step 1: Add Google Maps JavaScript API to Your Project
You first need to include the Google Maps API script in your HTML:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Google Maps Example</title>
    <script src="https://maps.googleapis.com/maps/api/js?key=YOUR_API_KEY"></script>
    <style>
        #map {
            height: 500px;
            width: 100%;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

<div id="map"></div>

<script>
    function initMap() {
        // Set the map's center and zoom level.
        var mapOptions = {
            center: {lat: 34.0522, lng: -118.2437}, // Los Angeles
            zoom: 10
        };

        // Create a new map and attach it to the div with id 'map'.
        var map = new google.maps.Map(document.getElementById('map'), mapOptions);

        // Example: Add a marker on the map
        var marker = new google.maps.Marker({
            position: {lat: 34.0522, lng: -118.2437},
            map: map,
            title: 'Los Angeles'
        });

        // You can add a layer or custom imagery if you have specific historical tiles
        // This is assuming you have your own historical imagery source:
        var historicalTileLayer = new google.maps.ImageMapType({
            getTileUrl: function(coord, zoom) {
                // URL where historical imagery is hosted
                return `https://your-historical-tiles.com/tiles/${zoom}/${coord.x}/${coord.y}.png`;
            },
            tileSize: new google.maps.Size(256, 256),
            name: 'Historical Imagery',
            maxZoom: 18
        });

        map.mapTypes.set('historical', historicalTileLayer);
        map.setMapTypeId('historical'); // Optional, set it as default
    }

    // Initialize the map
    initMap();
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

### Key Considerations:
- Replace `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual Google Maps API key.
- The image tile URL should point to a valid PNG tile source if you plan to include custom imagery.
- If you're trying to visualize changes over time and have specific datasets available, consider using a combination of image overlays at different times (historical layers).

For the most current and detailed information about Google Maps API capabilities, always refer to the [official documentation](https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/javascript/overview). If Google introduces a "time travel" feature in the future, the documentation will provide precise guidance on how to utilize it.
